2026-04-21 01:32:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6 + input cable/terminal'] hypothesis_explanation='By bridging Control Module 5’s + output directly to Control Module 7’s + input, bypassing Control Module 6’s + path, the internal indicator lamp and main load lamp both turned on with all switches closed. This proves that all modules downstream of 5 and the load module are functional and wired correctly, and that the battery and upstream modules 1–5 are also supplying 12 V properly. The only configuration that explains the initial symptoms (PSU LED on, all control LEDs missing, and lamp off) together with the positive bypass test is that Control Module 6’s series + conductor is open at its input side: the “floating” Control Input Cable (+) 6 noted during inspection corresponds to an unconnected/disconnected + terminal. This open circuit at Control Module 6’s + input prevents 12 V from reaching modules 6–8 and the load in the normal configuration. The root fault is therefore an open / disconnected + input cable or terminal on Control Module 6.'
